{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_jordan_ver01/data/sn91068401/00332892782/1938011001/0050.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWO\nHer Name Is Snowball\nr\ni>\nSnowball of Elmora, white kitten owned by Mrs. L. E. Kiernan, president\nof New Jersey State Cat Club, graciously\u2014if somewhat curiously\u2014con\n\u00ab\u00abnted to nose for her photograph. The occasion was the annual show of\nthe Atlantic Cat Club in New York City.\n(Central Press)\nKNUDSEN, BIGGERS AT WHITE HOUSE\nJ 5 J\ns g x y lillnl\n|w mn^\nsH I Ny-V vfo y\n1 11 Mp y L 'j- \"M'/T'a r\nA tit- .4*-\nJohn D. Diggers and William S. Knudsen\nJohn D. Biggers, left, director of the unemployment, census, and\nWilliam S. Knudsen, president of General Motors, visit t ;the' White\nHouse for a discussion of the president's proposal for industrial static\nlization of production through conferences between the government\nand business concerns. Appearing before it special senate eptnnfllt\ntee investigating causes of the business recession, Knudsen predicted\nthat there would be a business upturn by spring. Biggers, m private\nlife, is president of a large glass company at Toledo, O.\n\u2014C etiiVa: Press\nU. Navy Bomber Mining at Sea\nV.\nCadet Philip O. Browning Lieut. T. E. Carpenter\nfi\n\u00abfi\u00bbgA^.v.;: v.v. *oc.\n\nType of bombing plane missing\n.This type of U. S. navy bombing plane disappeared in the Pacific\noff San Diego with seven aboard. The plane, a twin-motored bomber,\nwas attached to the VP-7 squadron, which last year won a trophy\nfor the finest safety record. The plane was on \u201csecurity patrol\"\nwhen it disappeared. Two of those aboard are shown. They are\nXieut. T. E. Carpenter of Passumpsic, Vt., the pilot, and Cadet Philip\nO. Browning of Lees Summit, Mo.\n\u2014Central Press\nHENDERSON, <N. C.) DAILY DISPATCH MONDAY, JANUARY 10, 1938\n*v\nNew York\u2019s Ace Gardeners\nr Jmgp ||M||i\n1,.:\u00ae Wmiii\u00dfr x Wk\nJ|^\nHI jISL\nMMgj\u00df /jBBHiB\ns f itWW\u2122\nlllllv. ililp H&\nHolding their trophy and a sample of their prize celery are the Mullen\nsisters, Zelda (left) and Louise, of Stafford, N. Y., after they had been\nacclaimed champion gardeners of the New York State 4-H Clubs for\n1937, The award was mad\u00a9 at the annual Potato and Vegetable Growers\nAssociation in Syracuse. (Central Press)\nTough Guys and Their Molls\nGeorge McNulty, 27, and Jimmy Shearer, 16, are shown doing justice to\nsandwiches after their arrest with Betty McGoff and Mae McEldowney\n(both below), both 15 years old, in a vacant cottage near Patchogue,\nL. I. The boys claimed membership in an \u201cX Gang\u201d in Brooklyn, and\ndisplayed brands on their hands to prove how tough they are.\n(Central Press)\nAN EX-QUEEN GETS A NEW PALACE IN RUMANIA\nm\u00a7m i i.: illlill\u00dfiMfr\\:i BM^Miiiiir\"^\nrnmm 3\nv :wk :i\nOH isl\nB mm J M$k, n JH\nHjH mlh iflKij\nEx-Queen Elizabeth of Greece, King of Rumania and Queen Marie of Jugoslavia\nKing Carol of Rumania sits between his two sisters,\nex-Queen Elizabeth of Greece, left, and Queen\nMarie of Jugoslavia, in Bucharest at dedication\nceremonies of a new palace built for Elizabeth by\nthe Rumanian people. This ceremony took place\nonly a short time before Magda Lupescu, King\nOverruled!\nJL^i\nSm? MmmMMm\nm JWBIHf y B\nK -x-:---::\njjjs\u00df\n\nJustice George Sutherland of the\nUnited States Supreme Court ob\njected to the cameraman\u2019s motion,\nbut he was respectfully overruled.\nThis picture was snapped at Wash\nington, as he entered his home after\nthe news of his resignation from\nthe bench had been announced\n(Central >\u201cJ\nDenounces C. I. O.\nK tyWZs&ji- ::^^am\nWjftMfc mm: WMMi&mrm\n'-Jy\nl MmjMs\nMayor Frank Hague, of Jersey\nCity, N. J., is shown addressing a\nmeeting of 15,000 persons in the\nJersey City armory, where he d\u00a9-;\nfended his stand against the C. I. 0.,\nand reaffirmed his pledge to \"keep\nthe C. I. 0. and other un-American\ngroups\u201d out of the city.\n(Central Press)\nJ v aro I S l d ha i red swe ethe rt was forced to leave\nf C \u00b0r, ry dUe to J l e of Nationalistic, anti-Se\nm Great Britain and France have\nSprP<,^ P i s tat .I\u00b0ns 1 ns to Rumania to protect the\ne ZtoS 1 BU reStrlCti T the\nj Central Press\nDoesn\u2019t like License Plate\nv '^WMf\u2018\u2018\u25a0 w w\nMartin Mc\u00dfohin, of White Plains, N. Y\u201e didn\u2019t like the legend. \u201cNew\nYork World\u2019s Fair 1939\u201d which appears on the New York State license\nelates for 1938, so he taped out the offending ad for the fair. He was\narrested and charged with obscuring license plates. Mc\u00dfohin claims he\nhas sole right to decide what his car will advertise, and will defend his\nright, even carrying the fight to the Supreme Court if necessary.\nShe Saw a Policeman Killed\nHigh- x v\nBilii I\n>:\u25a0:\u25a0:.^<3&*^;fl\u00df2Siw;g?&<\u00ab>oo <^^'x>)r <ov^ij^i^wy^woSSgowg\u00bbra\nDetectives are shown calming the hysterical hat check girl at the McElroy\nCase in New York City after the attempted holdup in which Patrolman\nrrank Zaccor was shot to death. The policeman surprised three thugs\nas they were searching patrons of the restaurant. He was shot down,\nbut managed to shoot one of the bandits before he died. The other\ntwo escaped. (Central Press)\nPatchwork 8C Pup\ny^:\nm||M||py N\nX 4\n\nBeach costumes in winter resort*\n*re nothing if not colorful. Here is\nGloria Baker, New York\u2019s No. 1\nsociety girl, in a crazyjama outfit\n-at Palm Beach, strolling with her\npet dog.\nPanay Punishment\nBst&\nVice Admiral Kiyoshl Ilasegaw*\nSpeculation is rife as to who will\nbe appointed by President Roose\nvelt to the supreme court bench\nto succeed Justice George Suther\nland, conservative, who has an\nnounced his retirement -for Jan.\n16. Justice Sutherland gave his\nadvancing age\u201476\u2014\u00aend a recur\nring stomach ailment a* the\nreason.","height":"28266","width":"21303"}}
